{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:17:19.907447+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"issues\":[{\"number\":1,\"title\":\"Rate limit allows ~2x configured rate when bursting\",\"body\":\"Hi — I\\u0026#39;m using ratelimit-redis to protect a Flask endpoint. I configured capacity=10, refill_per_sec=10/60 (target: 10 requests per minute per IP), but I\\u0026#39;m seeing more like 20 requests per minute slip through under burst.\\n\\nReproducer:\\n\\n    # examples/flask_app.py as shipped\\n    while true; do curl http://localhost:5000/; sleep 0.5; done\\n\\nWithin 60 seconds I count roughly 20 successful (200) responses with the default `capacity=10` from the example, before the 429s kick in.\\n\\nMy read is the algorithm is correct (looking at bucket.lua), but the *example* might be misconfigured: `refill_per_sec=10/60` keeps refilling tokens during the burst, so after the initial 10-burst is consumed, a steady ~10 more tokens are refilled over the same minute. So the burst + refill = ~20 in the first 60s. The README copy makes it sound like the demo enforces 10/min hard.\\n\\nIs this intentional (token bucket vs leaky bucket framing) or is the example wrong?\\n\\nratelimit-redis 0.1.0\\nredis 7.2.4\",\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"user\":{\"login\":\"BruceKZ\"},\"created_at\":\"2026-05-22T01:05:12Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-05-22T01:05:12Z\"}],\"totalCount\":1,\"pageInfo\":{\"hasNextPage\":false,\"hasPreviousPage\":false,\"startCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQwMTowNToxMlrPAAAAAQwoeCg=\",\"endCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQwMTowNToxMlrPAAAAAQwoeCg=\"}}", "id": "lc_a5886e4c-ab6e-4f48-8153-52f69b2d0acb"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "list_issues", "id": "bf4b7702-c6a5-4e7a-ad01-3b83a7716f3c", "tool_call_id": "call_00_AYL3KcZAfH5EEN5gWdcs2719", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
